** Currently have no good way to tell a client _why_ their transaction failed. All client gets is Accepted & Finalized messages
   - Send PrepareResponse messages to originatingClient (allows 1RTT notice of successful commit in common case)
   - Consider adding error-handling info to TxResolution message sent by TxDriver to the client
   - Can describe why Abort was chosen for resolution
   - Use Option[], no need to send this info to other stores, only the client
   
** Add VersionLock & RefcountLocks to txd & store
   - These can be shared between Tx. No need for exclusive access
   - Will mean that Tx conflicts needs to be a list of transactions though
   
** Add Container Object Support to txd & store
   
** DataStore Transfers
   - Shut down store
   - Update store location to point at new host
   - Copy all CRL entries to separate file & delete from CRL DB
   - Send TAR of crl state + all data store files
   - Extract files, load CRL and it's up and running
   
** Live DataStore Transfers
   * Put store in Read-Only mode
   * Instantaneously transfer ownership to new host
   * Host forwards reads to old node while state transfer is in progress
   * Use the RAM-Only DataStore backend to maintain a durable in-mem copy of all modified objects while StoreTransfer is in progress
   * Load new DataStore
   * Begin process of write cached object to new store + delete from in-mem db
   * When all objects are removed, transfer is complete

** RAM-Only DataStore
   - Can be implemented on top of BufferredConsistentRocksDB
   - On start, load all kv w/ visit method
   - Eschews most of the complexity of the RocksDBStore impl
   
** Consider refactoring RocksDBDataStore into a generic Key-Value data store that takes an object with an API
   similar to that of BufferedConsistentRocksDB
   
** Error handling approaches
   - Can differ for different pools
   - Per-node error logs (like before)
   - Foster objects
   - Scanning
       - Background task periodically scans alloc trees and repairs nodes
   - Bitmask
       - Optimized variant of per-node error log
       - For mem-only, fixed-sized objects could maintain a bitmask for all peer stores
       - Set bits for suspected misses
   
System-Level FinalizationAction handlers
  * Not all Finalizers are appropriate for running in the core system. Take end-user code, for example.
  * Rather than requiring the storage nodes to understand all finalizers, we could instead have a
    finalizer service that could be leveraged to execute the FA on the storge node's behalf. Possibly
    as end-user code within a dedicated container
  * Tie this in with the client application having hte primary responsibility for executing the FA.
  * Storage nodes only do this as a fallback if the client heartbeat of "im still working on the FAs" stops
  
Security Model
  * Foundation is each message has associated client UUID 
  * Client either does or does not have read/write access to a pool
  * Network layer is responsible for ensuring this is reliable
  * Leverage graph model to reduce/eliminate searching
  * Pools are aggregated into PoolAuthGroups (so pools with same creds can be aggregated)
  * PoolAuthGroups point to individual clients and/or CertAuthAuthorities
  * Storage nodes pre-load cred info on startup for all PoolAuthGroups referenced by its hosted pools
  
# --------------- Architecture ---------------

* Core package is message-handling centric.
  * only generated messages are in response to other messages
      |-> TransactionDriver subclasses are the only classes that generate messages and these will still
          generally only be responses. The only truly "generated" messages are from Paxos error recovery
          e.g. lost messages, leadership collisions, etc
          
  * Transaction, Allocation, & Read are all implemented with Managers and Drivers. Each operation gets a
    UUID and a driver instance drives the operation to completion.
          
  
* Transaction
   - Fills the Acceptor & Learner Paxos roles
   - Interacts with a DataStore to vote on whether or not a transaction should be committed
   - Interacts with the CrashRecovery Handler to ensure transaction state is not lost
   - Locks the object(s) to the Transaction if voting for commit
   - Ensures DataStore can CRL state is cleaned up when the transaction completes
    
* TransactionDriver
   - Fills Proposer & Learner roles Paxos.
   - Receives TxPrepared, TxAccepted and sends Prepare/Accept msgs
   - Created for designatedLeader nodes
   - Created for recovery of Tx with failed leader
   - Create via factory object passed to TxManager
   - Totally encapsulates the retransmit/retry logic
   		
      
      
BackLog

Error Handling:
   * Allocation - Need an AllocationResolutionStrategy mixin. Currently BaseAllocationManager is best-effort only and leaks storage on failed
                  allocations while the store is offline (only uses TxResolved/TxFinalized) messages.
                  
   * Transaction
       - Failed leader detection
       - Recovery
           - In progress
           - After commit/abort w/ cached response
           - After commit w/ lastTxUUID = in-progress TxUUID
           - After commit w/different last committed txUUID
           - Same commit + version bump
           
   * Refuse to vote on transaction if any FinalizationAction is unknown
   
** Potential Read enhancement
   - When reading an object that's locked for update, send both current and locked data
   - Reader can then determine whether locked or current data is the most recent and return accordingly

* Allocation trees use same IDA as their StoragePoolDefinition node and all tree nodes are stored on the pool itself
   - This will need to be configurable
   - Will need to update isIDASupported() method to return false when requested IDA is more reliable than the alloc tree
   - also missing a way to specify the tree object size

* Add special messages for "PartiallyAccepted" and "SuccessfullyCommitted"
   |-> Use these in lieu of the normal messages if the crash recovery log is down. Peers use these to avoid
       adding recovery entries for transactions successfully processed.